result.execSummary:
The defendant Bridgette M Manning was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes:
Pay a fine of $140 plus mandatory costs, assessments and surcharges by 7-1-17 or a civil judgment is to be entered against the defendant and subject to other collection.

COURT ORDERS:
- defendant to provide a DNA sample and pay the surcharge.

*Court advises the defendant any possession or use of any illegally controlled substance or alcohol forfeits the release privileges.

COURT ORDERS defendant to serve 10 months at the House of Correction - consecutive - the first 5 days are to be straight time - the balance can be with release privileges for the Day Reporting Program - no objection to electronic monitoring while in the program - any violation will revoke the program and 63 days credit;

Court advises the defendant she may not possess a firearm; is to provide a DNA sample and pay the surcharge and cannot vote until her civil rights are restored.  

If the defendant possesses a firearm within 5 years of the completion of this sentence, she will be subject to a 3 year mandatory initial confinement.
